WEBVTT

00:03.828 --> 00:04.629
Okay.

00:04.649 --> 00:21.035
Well, let me just count that statement by saying that don't forget that there are any number of collectors over the past who have had merchandise delivered to them by booksellers and not asked the bookseller into the house.

00:21.055 --> 00:23.078
Yeah, but everybody wanted to see who this guy was.

00:23.218 --> 00:26.624
Everybody wanted to, but that doesn't necessarily mean that he has to comply.

00:26.644 --> 00:30.730
But he was just delivering the first portfolio of Shakespeare and he had just come up from New York.

00:30.710 --> 00:31.773
I know.

00:31.873 --> 00:37.286
And it's not an unreasonable request to want to go and use the mention.

00:37.467 --> 00:39.592
No, I'm saying that's unreasonable.

00:39.612 --> 00:44.644
I'm saying that behavior is unreasonable, but it is not unknown.

00:44.905 --> 00:47.892
And I have known collectors in England.

00:48.192 --> 00:58.750
who would just take delivery of a valuable book at the door, and you were expected not to come in.

00:58.950 --> 01:00.413
And that was that.

01:01.534 --> 01:09.488
There's a certain area here of tradesmen and gentlemen.

01:10.029 --> 01:11.631
You may not understand that.

01:12.052 --> 01:13.795
On the other hand, let me interject.

01:14.062 --> 01:23.215
Haven actively sought out the company of other collectors, of booksellers, book people such as yourself.

01:23.235 --> 01:32.508
We actively sought their company and sought ways to be invited to their homes and then used John Fleming to get invitations.

01:34.050 --> 01:38.597
I'm sure getting to your house that night was kind of a cool thing.

01:38.617 --> 01:39.878
No, I shouldn't think so.

01:39.899 --> 01:40.980
No, not the slightest thing.

01:41.365 --> 01:43.730
Just a minor, very much a minor figure.

01:43.750 --> 01:45.694
No, he associated with booksellers.

01:46.055 --> 01:48.921
I don't think he associated with collectors until later on.

01:49.802 --> 01:53.330
I think he may have, I don't know, when the episode of Shidey took place.

01:53.670 --> 01:53.991
Late.

01:54.275 --> 02:01.003
Blake, yeah, well he also, if you remember, he got involved with the Blake things.

02:01.023 --> 02:03.827
Nicholas Bartle will fill you in on the works.

02:03.847 --> 02:09.113
Geoffrey Caines and this and that, sure.

02:09.193 --> 02:13.238
Anyway, it was a great, great film.

02:13.278 --> 02:20.367
And if he'd gone on for 30 odd years, it would have been an immeasurably greater film.

02:20.587 --> 02:21.328
Did you know...

02:21.511 --> 02:25.897
Did you ever have any dealings with Michael Davis's father, Leonard Davis?

02:26.238 --> 02:26.578
Not at all, no.

02:26.598 --> 02:27.800
Do you know who Leonard Davis is?

02:27.820 --> 02:28.060
No.

02:28.621 --> 02:33.528
I heard of Michael Davis only at the time when we did the appraisal.

02:33.909 --> 02:44.224
And I think I must have seen Michael Davis's name on an invoice delivered to Michael Davis.

02:44.304 --> 02:46.066
I think it was an H.P.

02:46.367 --> 02:47.248
Crown invoice.

02:47.600 --> 02:55.511
And I heard, I heard of Michael Davis from Thorne Weldon, who worked for John Fleming.

02:55.531 --> 02:57.253
He now works at Journal Street.

02:57.333 --> 02:58.996
I know, yeah.

02:59.276 --> 03:00.097
You've had lunch with him.

03:00.117 --> 03:08.629
Good, because I heard from Thorne, I mean, quite innocent.

03:09.048 --> 03:11.912
Thorne's not a child, she's a woman.

03:12.332 --> 03:16.017
And Thorne said, my God, yeah, we all remembered Michael Davis.

03:16.117 --> 03:17.159
His nickname was Fox.

03:17.419 --> 03:19.462
Well, I don't know.

03:20.163 --> 03:26.592
She said we used to party with Michael here in New York in 1974 and five.

03:27.873 --> 03:28.474
Why not?

03:28.657 --> 03:34.242
She was, however old she would have been then, she would have been 19 or 20, I suppose.

03:35.283 --> 03:35.623
So fine.

03:36.684 --> 03:38.986
It's an amazing story, isn't it?

03:39.006 --> 03:41.048
It's an amazing story.

03:41.088 --> 03:42.970
Well, you know more about that than I do.

03:43.330 --> 03:44.731
What's the outcome of the suit?

03:44.751 --> 03:47.994
What's the outcome of the suit?

03:48.014 --> 03:51.397
Did you know that his name is probably 19 or more?

03:51.838 --> 03:54.320
Well, yes, I knew that, but I didn't know what the name was.

03:54.820 --> 03:56.202
Do you know now?

03:56.522 --> 03:56.622
Nope.

03:56.642 --> 03:57.803
I didn't have an idea.

03:58.508 --> 04:01.553
No, not from memory, I don't.

04:01.653 --> 04:05.560
How did you know that it wasn't his name?

04:07.704 --> 04:10.809
I think it was mentioned by Arthur Houghton to me.

04:10.829 --> 04:15.998
No, he didn't know the name, but there were just a number of people.

04:16.078 --> 04:17.040
Yeah, that's right.

04:17.695 --> 04:18.336
That's right.

04:18.356 --> 04:20.478
That's the title of that chapter, by the way.

04:21.619 --> 04:22.340
Have No More.

04:23.841 --> 04:24.482
No, sure.

04:24.522 --> 04:24.982
Have No More.

04:25.022 --> 04:25.923
So what was his name?

04:26.123 --> 04:27.765
I haven't worked with him.

04:27.785 --> 04:29.607
Oh, you still don't know him?

04:29.647 --> 04:30.648
Shackley Product.

04:30.668 --> 04:31.569
Shackley Product.

04:31.889 --> 04:33.111
This is years ago.

04:33.171 --> 04:40.518
Speculation of various sorts about background of his money.

04:40.958 --> 04:46.504
One of the things he told me was that it developed...

04:46.906 --> 04:53.057
a guidance system for Polaris missiles and sold it to the government.

04:53.077 --> 04:59.709
And that had us wreathed in smiles for a number of months.

04:59.729 --> 05:01.011
Shaq and Fredericks?

05:01.032 --> 05:02.434
Shaq, he told you that name?

05:02.870 --> 05:05.614
No, I think somebody, I think I heard it around here.

05:05.634 --> 05:06.255
I'll check it out.

05:06.495 --> 05:08.238
You can, sure.

05:08.498 --> 05:10.441
And then I heard that his wife had money.

05:11.182 --> 05:12.023
She's from Arkansas.

05:12.103 --> 05:12.945
Harris from Arkansas.

05:12.965 --> 05:16.670
Yeah, well, I heard on the grapevine that she had money.

05:16.690 --> 05:20.576
None of these things meant anything when we heard about Michael Davis.

05:20.596 --> 05:25.923
As soon as we heard about Michael Davis, we then said, ah, that's the source of his money.

05:26.164 --> 05:26.764
That's fine.

05:27.125 --> 05:29.248
One other quick thing.

05:29.515 --> 05:34.924
Did he tell you where he went to school?

05:34.944 --> 05:35.204
No.

05:35.224 --> 05:41.394
On the 1980s and the 1990s, was the 1980s a new golden age in bookselling and book collecting?

05:41.434 --> 05:51.731
As David Redden has asserted, and as Ed Wolff said, he said, well, I didn't see any picklet papers, not picklet papers, Paul Richard Alman, actually.

05:52.372 --> 05:53.434
You know, a golden age.

05:53.514 --> 05:56.198
He said, we'd love to have a complete set of books.

05:56.600 --> 06:05.429
I guess what he's saying is that there's some wonderful things available, but you still couldn't, by the way, Huntington was able to buy 70, 80 years ago.

06:06.470 --> 06:12.776
But nevertheless, there were some marvelous things because of the changes in the tax laws and the institutions.

06:12.796 --> 06:14.338
Not getting the material that they want.

06:14.578 --> 06:17.941
That's a very dry, unfocused state.

06:17.961 --> 06:21.865
But maybe if you could just give me a comment on the 80s and what you see in the 90s.

06:21.885 --> 06:23.687
How's that?

06:23.903 --> 06:42.300
My view of the thought of high prices and big time auctions really starts in November 1985.

06:42.360 --> 06:50.788
It's the first time we had a general miscellaneous consigned sale.

06:51.477 --> 06:54.741
from various owners that was 100% sold across the board.

06:54.781 --> 07:06.455
There seemed at that time to be a situation where everything just sold at Auckland.

07:06.475 --> 07:08.357
Everything sold and for very high prices.

07:09.178 --> 07:11.440
There had been great sales with us before.

07:13.243 --> 07:15.325
Some of our greatest sales, namely

07:16.098 --> 07:28.690
the Chew Sale in 1982, in which we had the original manuscript of the Mason-Dixon line, and the Declaration of Independence, and the Charter for Pennsylvania.

07:30.256 --> 07:32.078
A sale like that made $800,000.

07:32.258 --> 07:39.105
A sale like that today would bring $5 million.

07:39.125 --> 07:39.686
Even today?

07:40.106 --> 07:43.490
I'm saying today, from 82 to 91, it would bring $5 million.

07:43.530 --> 07:57.705
Today, well, assuming that a copy of the Declaration of Independence belonging to Justice Chew with an impeccable provenance, it's got to bring as much as the last one, mate, I would have thought.

07:57.725 --> 07:59.166
Which nobody knows what to know.

07:59.770 --> 08:01.232
Any theories on that?

08:03.394 --> 08:04.996
Do you think it was found in a free market?

08:05.737 --> 08:06.899
No, I don't know.

08:07.940 --> 08:08.721
You want me to guess?

08:08.781 --> 08:09.642
No, I don't think so.

08:10.283 --> 08:12.205
I think it came out of an archive.

08:12.245 --> 08:15.569
Most of them come out of archives.

08:16.310 --> 08:21.717
The Corn Leary copy emerged in a bookstore, which is possible.

08:21.837 --> 08:29.406
The Corn Leary copy that was sold in 1969, it was at Leary's bookstore in Philadelphia for many, many years.

08:29.791 --> 08:32.033
before being sold in 1969.

08:33.895 --> 08:41.462
The copy that we sold for the Chew family was discovered in the archive in 1972.

08:41.542 --> 08:46.046
The copy in the Chew family archive.

08:46.407 --> 08:59.359
The copy we sold for the Wood family in North Carolina from Edenton was discovered in a family archive in about 1981.

08:59.457 --> 09:07.164
and it was shown to Freddie Goff, he showed it to me, and we sold it a year after the two, the two copy.

09:07.184 --> 09:22.039
But what I'm saying is that... Tuck, tuck, tuck behind a picture frame, and you can't find the picture frame, and the picture's gone, and then it's taken two years to sell it from the sale.

09:22.059 --> 09:24.822
And the owner, we don't know who the owner is either, the consignor.

09:24.962 --> 09:25.262
No.

09:26.137 --> 09:28.542
The whole thing is strange.

09:28.562 --> 09:30.988
And yet it's a heck of a beautiful coffee.

09:31.008 --> 09:36.400
Well, there's nothing wrong with it being a beautiful coffee, but they often are beautiful.

09:36.600 --> 09:42.393
The Chew coffee and the wood coffee that we sold were equally beautiful.

09:42.934 --> 09:45.580
The magnificent coffees, you can just see pictures of them in a

09:45.863 --> 09:46.965
in the catalogs.

09:46.985 --> 09:48.347
I mean, they were brilliant copies.

09:48.367 --> 09:49.729
They were quite as good as that one.

09:49.749 --> 09:55.257
When you say an archive, you think a private archive or an institutional archive that hasn't been catalogued?

09:55.277 --> 09:57.901
I haven't any idea.

09:57.921 --> 09:59.363
I have no idea.

09:59.383 --> 10:01.487
I mean, now let's talk briefly about texts.

10:01.507 --> 10:02.408
I guess we'd have to go.

